'''Wanikawa Shrine''' (わにかわじんじゃ) is a {{ill|lt=Shinto shrine|Q845945|WD=Q845945|1=Shinto shrine}} in {{ill|lt=Miki, Kagawa|Q1205980|WD=Q1205980|1=Miki, Kagawa}}, {{ill|lt=Kita District|Q1155929|WD=Q1155929|1=Kita District, Kagawa}}, {{ill|lt=Kagawa Prefecture|Q161454|WD=Q161454|1=Kagawa Prefecture}}. It is one of the candidate shrines for Wanigawa Shrine, a {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=Shikinaisha|1=Shikinaisha|WD=Q134917286}} of Takaoka-go, {{ill|lt=Miki District|Q10866143|WD=Q10866143|1=Miki district}}, {{ill|lt=Sanuki Province|Q929682|WD=Q929682|1=Sanuki Province}}. It is one of the “Sanuki Fifteen Shrines.”

There is a theory that {{ill|lt=Hakusan Shrine (Miki)|Q11579589|WD=Q11579589|lt=Hakusan Shrine|1=Hakusan Shrine (Q11579589)}}, also a candidate shrine for Wanigawa Shrine, is an outside branch shrine of Wanikawa Shrine.

=== Enshrined deities ===
*{{ill|WD=Q2329261|lt=Toyotama-hime|Q2329261|WD=Q2329261|WD=Q2329261|lt=Toyotama-hime-no-Mikoto|1=Toyotama-hime}}
*{{ill|lt=Emperor Ōjin|Q317997|WD=Q317997|1=Emperor Ōjin}}

=== Outline ===
The founding period is unknown. According to shrine tradition, {{ill|UNKNOWN|WD=Q2329261|lt=Toyotama-hime-no-Mikoto|1=Toyotama-hime}} rode a {{ill|lt=sea turtle|Q30143|WD=Q30143|lt=turtle|1=Cheloniidae}} ashore at Kata-moto in {{ill|lt=Yamada District (Kagawa)|Q11046466|WD=Q11046466|lt=Yamada District|1=Yamada district}}, {{ill|lt=Sanuki Province|Q929682|WD=Q929682|1=Sanuki Province}} (near {{ill|lt=Yashima|Q11465681|WD=Q11465681|1=Yashima}}), gave birth to {{ill|lt=Ugayafukiaezu|Q1373935|WD=Q1373935|lt=Ugayafukiaezu-no-Mikoto|1=Ugayafukiaezu}} there, then rode a {{ill|lt=wani|Q11674313|WD=Q11674313|1=wani}} upstream and landed here.

There is also a tradition that {{ill|lt=Gyōki|Q1136664|WD=Q1136664|1=Gyōki}} founded it here.

In {{ill|lt=Engi|Q1374325|WD=Q1374325|1=Engi (era)}} 7 ({{ill|lt=907|Q24163|WD=Q24163|1=907}}), the {{ill|lt=Hachiman deity|Q261637|WD=Q261637|1=Hachiman}} was enshrined as an associated deity, and it was also called Takaoka Hachiman. Through {{ill|lt=shinbutsu shūgō|Q2279088|WD=Q2279088|1=Shinbutsu-shūgō}}, Ōjin-ji was also founded as its {{ill|lt=bettōji|Q11396755|WD=Q11396755|1=Bettō-ji}}.

In {{ill|lt=Meiji|Q3125096|WD=Q3125096|1=Meiji era}} 1 ({{ill|lt=1868|Q7717|WD=Q7717|1=1868}}), Ōjin-ji was abolished in the {{ill|lt=separation of Shinto and Buddhism|Q1970535|WD=Q1970535|1=Shinbutsu bunri}}. In Meiji 5 ({{ill|lt=1872|Q7753|WD=Q7753|1=1872}}), it was renamed Wanikawa Shrine and became {{ill|lt=gōsha|Q134917316|WD=Q134917316|1=Gō-sha}}.

=== Other ===
* The lion head for Wanikawa Shrine’s {{ill|lt=lion dance|Q713866|WD=Q713866|1=Lion dance}} is 63 cm high, 90 cm wide, and 100 cm long; with the dance cloth, total length is about 13 m. This giant lion dance is moved by about 50 people and is a designated cultural property of Miki Town.
* The seated dry-lacquer {{ill|lt=Shō-Kannon|Q124684411|WD=Q124684411|1=Āryāvalokiteśvara}} statue at Gankō-ji in {{ill|lt=Sanuki|Q857202|WD=Q857202|1=Sanuki, Kagawa}} is said in tradition to have been the principal image of Ōjin-ji, the bettō temple of Wanikawa Shrine.
* The river that Toyotama-hime rode upstream on a wani later became Wani River, said to be today’s {{ill|lt=Shinkawa (Kagawa)|Q11502062|WD=Q11502062|lt=Shinkawa|1=Shinkawa River}}. According to nearby {{ill|lt=Wanigawa Shrine|Q11417869|WD=Q11417869|1=Wanikawa Shrine (Q11417869)}} (another candidate shrine), Wani River refers to {{ill|lt=Kamobe River|Q11675608|WD=Q11675608|1=Kabe River}}.

=== Access ===
* 20 minutes on foot from {{ill|lt=Hakusan Station (Kagawa)|Q11579619|WD=Q11579619|lt=Hakusan Station|1=Shirayama Station}} on the {{ill|lt=Nagao Line|Q5364831|WD=Q5364831|1=Kotoden Nagao Line}} of {{ill|lt=Takamatsu-Kotohira Electric Railroad|Q566998|WD=Q566998|1=Takamatsu-Kotohira Electric Railroad}}.

